{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chart-page-js","path":"/dot-plot","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>shows the distribution of individual observations represented as dots at regular intervals. Dots are placed as close to their position along the scale as possible but without overlapping other dots. </p>\n<!--more-->\n<p>Dot plots are displayed along an X-axis with an <strong><em>interval scale</em></strong> and a Y-axis that shows <strong><em>frequency</em></strong>.</p>\n<p>There are two types of dot plots: symmetric and asymmetric.</p>\n<p><em>Asymmetric dot plots</em> align the dot columns along the X-axis.\n<em>Symmetric dot plots</em> align the dots along their center on the Y-axis.</p>\n<p>Dot plots are similar to <a href=\"/histogram\">histogram</a>, but they are more accurate since the data has not been binned. For this reason, dot plots are considered a better starting point for getting a sense of the distribution of a variable than a histogram.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> </p>\n<p>Dot plots can be thought of as one-dimensional <a href=\"/scatter-plot\">scatter plots</a> positioned along the X-axis.</p>\n<p>Dot plots have a long history, but the first formal description comes from Leland Wilkinson who makes a distinction between the hand-drawn dot plots that placed dots as close as possible to their position on the X-axis and computer-drawn dot plots that simply <em>bin</em> dots as in a histogram. <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></p>\n<h2 id=\"alternatives\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#alternatives\" aria-label=\"alternatives permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Alternatives</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"/histogram\"><em>Histogram</em></a> bin individual observations and represent their quantities with bars of proportional heights.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/scatter-plot\"><em>Scatter plot</em></a> shows individual data points of bivariate (two-variable) data.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/strip-plot#beeswarm-plot\"><em>Beeswarm plot</em></a> shows individual data points along a single axis. It is typically used to compare several distributions.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/density-plot\"><em>Density plot</em></a> shows a density estimate of a distribution as a smooth curve.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/box-plot\"><em>Box plot</em></a> shows an overview of the distribution with median values, 25th, and 75th quartiles, and outliers but does not show actual data points. </li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"further-reading\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#further-reading\" aria-label=\"further reading permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Further reading</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_plot_(statistics)\">Dot plot</a> article on Wikipedia.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"references\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#references\" aria-label=\"references permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<hr>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"fn-1\">\n<p>Wilkinson, Leland. <a href=\"(https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&#x26;lr=&#x26;id=_kRX4LoFfGQC)\"><em>The Grammar of Graphics.</em></a> Springer Science &#x26; Business Media, 2005. p.316.</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-1\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-2\">\n<p>Wilkinson, Leland. <a href=\"https://www.cs.uic.edu/~wilkinson/Publications/dotplots.pdf\">\"Dot plots.\"</a> <em>The American Statistician</em> 53.3 (1999): 276-281. doi: 10.1080/00031305.1999.10474474 </p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-2\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>","excerpt":"shows the distribution of individual observations represented as dots at regular intervals. Dots are placed as close to their position along…","overview":"<p>shows the distribution of individual observations represented as dots at regular intervals. Dots are placed as close to their position along…</p>","fields":{"variationOf":null},"frontmatter":{"title":"dot plot","synonyms":null,"functions":["distribution"],"visualizationTechniques":[{"techniqueId":"REP","informationType":"quantity","axisDirection":null}],"informationTypes":null,"axisDirections":null,"examples":[{"title":"Every goal scored in the football World Cup by minute","link":"https://www.economist.com/node/21603828","note":null,"image":"every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup.png"}],"tools":[{"name":"D3.js","link":"https://bl.ocks.org/mbostock/3883195"},{"name":"Protovis","link":"http://mbostock.github.io/protovis/ex/histogram.html"},{"name":"Google Charts","link":"https://developers.google.com/chart/"},{"name":"Microsoft Excel","link":"https://office.microsoft.com"},{"name":"Apple Numbers","link":"https://www.apple.com/numbers"},{"name":"Google Docs","link":"https://docs.google.com"},{"name":"High Charts","link":"https://www.highcharts.com"},{"name":"R","link":"http://www.r-graph-gallery.com/83-histogram-with-colored-tail/"}]},"fileInfo":{"__typename":"File","modifiedTime":"07/24/2023"}},"coverImage":{"publicURL":"/static/b1b4fb55475cd5dff74e61af378881a2/cover.png"},"anatomyImage":{"publicURL":"/static/59267b787aa8ec8cc41c6d85d1e31e0b/anatomy.png"},"site":{"siteMetadata":{"siteUrl":"https://graphopedia.xyz"}},"exampleImages":{"edges":[{"node":{"base":"every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup.png","relativeDirectory":"charts/dot-plot/examples","childImageSharp":{"original":{"width":1992,"height":1382,"src":"/static/every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup-f0df83edc527c8cec6b70ff1a4009d73.png"},"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":300,"height":300,"src":"/static/f0df83edc527c8cec6b70ff1a4009d73/dc5e0/every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup.png","srcSet":"/static/f0df83edc527c8cec6b70ff1a4009d73/dc5e0/every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup.png 1x,\n/static/f0df83edc527c8cec6b70ff1a4009d73/3c5ef/every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup.png 1.5x,\n/static/f0df83edc527c8cec6b70ff1a4009d73/9847e/every-goal-scored-in-the-football-world-cup.png 2x"}}}}]},"variations":{"edges":[]},"parentChart":null,"allVisualizationTechniquesYaml":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"PIC","name":"picturing"}},{"node":{"id":"MAP","name":"mapping"}},{"node":{"id":"AXI","name":"positioning along a coordinate axis"}},{"node":{"id":"EXT","name":"extending along a coordinate axis"}},{"node":{"id":"DIV","name":"diverging along a coordinate axis"}},{"node":{"id":"RAN","name":"ranging along a coordinate axis"}},{"node":{"id":"TER","name":"ternary positioning along three axes"}},{"node":{"id"